Φ(PlayableEpist) = σ(legibility|feedback) ∘ ρ(embodiment|felt-knowledge) ∘ λ(iteration|agency) ∘ β(learnability|growth) ∘ δγ(sandbox|practice) ∘ μ(architecture|affordance) + ε | :optimized_learning

; === Operator Breakdown ===

; σ — Air / Aerunik (0.80)
;   Feedback density: immediate, granular, actionable signals that make the
;   learning environment legible. Games succeed because every action produces
;   visible consequences — the system tells you what happened, why it matters,
;   and what you might try next. Aerunik governs this transparency: the
;   conversion of opaque complexity into legible signal. Feedback density is
;   the air that makes the learning landscape visible.

; ρ — Water / Sentaria (0.73)
;   Embodied knowledge: skills that become felt and intuitive through repeated
;   practice. The fourth dimension of playability — embodied knowledge —
;   describes the moment when a skill stops being a consciously executed
;   procedure and becomes a fluid, felt capacity. Sentaria governs this
;   transition from cognitive to somatic, from knowing-that to knowing-how,
;   from thinking about to flowing through.

; λ — Fire / Jvalion (0.85)
;   The dominant operator. Experiential iteration — rapid cycles of
;   try-fail-adjust that preserve learner agency throughout. Games are
;   iteration engines: they invite action, provide consequences, and loop
;   the learner back to try again with new information. Jvalion fuels this
;   generative cycle — the restless, experimental energy that refuses passive
;   consumption. Agency is non-negotiable: the learner must feel that their
;   choices matter and that failure is a move in the game, not an exit from it.

; β — Wood / Arboriel (0.76)
;   Learnability as organic growth. Systems designed so that competence
;   develops naturally through engagement — not through instruction manuals
;   but through graduated challenges that meet the learner where they are.
;   Arboriel governs the developmental curve: the way a well-designed game
;   grows the player's skill organically, each level building on the last,
;   each new mechanic introduced at the moment of readiness.

; δγ — Earth / Humavita (0.71)
;   Sandbox grounding: safe practice environments where failure carries no
;   catastrophic cost. The sandbox is the earthen container that makes
;   experimentation possible — a bounded space where consequences are real
;   enough to teach but contained enough to permit risk. Humavita provides
;   the stable ground on which iterative play can occur without existential
;   anxiety about irreversible failure.

; μ — Metal / Ferrosid (0.79)
;   Affordance architecture: the structural design of action possibilities.
;   Affordances must be both explicit (what can I do here?) and discoverable
;   (what else might be possible?). Ferrosid encodes the design discipline
;   required to create systems where possibilities are clear without being
;   constraining — structured enough to guide, open enough to surprise.
;   The Memetic Simulation Engine and real-time feedback overlays require
;   this architectural precision.

; === Z-State ===
; Optimized learning — the system achieves maximum knowledge transfer through
; playable design. The gap between game-optimized learning (immediate feedback,
; clear affordances, safe iteration, embodied skill) and traditional
; sensemaking (delayed feedback, opaque structure, high-stakes failure,
; abstract knowledge) is bridged by making all learning environments playable.

; === Tendency ===
; λ → 0.85 — The system leans strongly toward iterative agency (fire). The
; primary mode is experimental: try, fail, adjust, try again. Learning
; happens through action, not reception. The fire of iteration drives all
; other elements into motion.

# CE-STATE: multiscale
# EI-NOTE: Causal power distributed across multiple description levels
